'''Mu-i''' (无位・無位, "Mu-i") refers to individuals without a {{ill|court rank|ja|位階}} under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制}}. This term often specifically denotes those who were employed in {{ill|Executive (government)|lt=government offices|ja|官司}} and held {{ill|Kanshoku|lt=official positions|ja|官職}} but did not possess a court rank.

== Overview ==
Under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制}}, the correlation between official positions and court ranks was defined by the {{ill|Rank-Position Correspondence System|ja|官位相当制|1=Kan'i sōtō system}}. However, some lower-level positions, particularly those classified as {{ill|Miscellaneous Officials|ja|雑任}}, were excluded from this system. This was particularly common for positions below the {{ill|Four-Tier System of Officials|ja|四等官}} and those not treated as {{ill|Pinkan|ja|品官}}.

For example:
- The {{ill|Department of Divinities|ja|神祇官|1=Department of Divinities|blank=}} had a total of 89 positions, but only seven were {{ill|Shikiji Officials|ja|職事官}} with corresponding ranks.
- The {{ill|City Offices (Tōji and Sai)|ja|市司}} each had 39 positions, but only three—Chief (Sei), Assistant (Yū), and Clerk (Reishi)—were Shikiji Officials. Positions ranked below Value Chief (Kaichō) were considered {{ill|Miscellaneous Officials|ja|雑任}} without corresponding ranks.

These Miscellaneous Officials included not only individuals with low ranks, such as {{ill|Shōi|ja|初位}} or {{ill|Hachi-i|ja|八位}}, but also individuals entirely without rank, referred to as "Mu-i."

References in legal texts like the {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老律令}} confirm the existence of Mu-i officials. For instance:
- The {{ill|Clothing Regulations (Ifuku-ryō)|ja|衣服令}} specified that Mu-i individuals were to wear yellow robes.
- The {{ill|Miscellaneous Regulations (Zatsu-ryō)|ja|雑令}} required Mu-i individuals to deliver one bundle of firewood as part of their obligations for the annual offerings on the 15th day of the New Year.

Mu-i officials were appointed to Miscellaneous Official positions through the prescribed procedures. They sought opportunities for promotion or acquisition of rank through diligence and accumulation of merit. While some were fortunate enough to be granted ranks through the {{ill|Merit Evaluation|ja|考課}} process, this opportunity was limited, and many aspects of their actual circumstances remain unclear.

== References ==
* {{ill|Takashi Umemura|ja|梅村喬}}, "The Ancient Governmental System and 'Shoku'," in *The Formation Process of the 'Shoku'* (校倉書房, 2011) ISBN 978-4-7517-4360-7.

